@NODE WhatIs "What's it all about then?"

 Qwk2Pkt converts Qwk off-line mail packets into FidoNet compatible .PKT
files.  You may want to do this for several reasons.  My main reason for
writing the program was because a BBS that I called for a certain echo only
had off-line mail facilities (no front-end mailer s/w at all).  The problem
was that I could not find any OLR software that satisfied my needs.

 Now that I have the messages in .PKT format, I can use the excellent point
program: Spot!  The limitations at the moment are that you can't convert the
other way just yet, but Watch This Space!

 To use it, just unarchive your .QWK mail packet and copy MESSAGES.DAT and
CONTROL.DAT to the directory where you want the .PKT to be written.  Note 
that you must run the program from the same directory as the MESSAGES.DAT 
and CONTROL.DAT files.

 Another feature of Qwk2Pkt is that it capitalizes names (many QWK programs
put names into uppercase).  Qwk2Pkt will properly capitalize names such
as "McGee" if you request (the correct version must appear in
ENV:Qwk2Pkt.names; see @{" template " link Usage}).

 That's it, now read about the command @{" template " link Usage} !

@ENDNODE
@NODE Installation "Installing Qwk2Pkt"

 Installation is simple; no script is supplied.

 Copy Qwk2Pkt.names to ENVARC:
 Copy Qwk2Pkt to C: (or wherever you like: MAIL:bin)

 (Qwk2Pkt.names should be copied to ENV: when booting)

@ENDNODE
