@NODE Usage "Using Qwk2Pkt from the CLI"

 Qwk2Pkt may only be run from a CLI.  The argument template is as follows:

 FROMADDR/A,TOADDR/A,BUF=BUFSIZE/N,NOREQ/S,NOCAP/S,CN=CORRECTNAME/S


 FROMADDR/A             You must specify this argument.  It should be in 
                        the format of a FidoNet address, for example:

                        2:441/93.42

                        If the point part of the address is zero, you may 
                        omit it, eg: 2:441/93 is the same as 2:441/93.0

                        This is the address that will be placed in the 
                        relevant "from" parts of the packet header.  If
                        Qwk2Pkt comes across a message without an Origin 
                        line, a default one will be created (along with a
                        tearline) and this address will be placed in it.


  TOADDR/A              You must specify this argument.  As above, this must 
                        be in the format of a FidoNet address.

                        This address will be placed in the relevant "to" 
                        parts of the packet header.


  BUF=BUFSIZE/N         This must be a positive integer that is greater than 
                        4096.  This argument is optional.

                        This argument allows you to specify the buffer sizes
                        for the CONTROL.DAT, MESSAGES.DAT and packet files 
                        (this can greatly speed things up).

                        I run a 68000 processor and I find that a buffer of 
                        about 32K works a treat.  Experiment to find the 
                        best value for your system setup.


  NOREQ/S               If present on the command line, AmigaDOS requesters
                        will be turned off for Qwk2Pkt (read/write error
                        requesters etc.)  This switch is of main use to 
                        people who leave their system unattended.


  NOCAP/S               This switch is used to turn off name capitalisation.
                        (Although note that many Qwk doors put users names
                        into uppercase).

  CN=CORRECTNAME/S      This switch is used to enable proper name correction
                        for names such as "McGee".  By default, they would
                        be converted to "Mcgee".  For this feature to work
                        the correct version of the name must be in the
                        "ENV:Qwk2Pkt.names" file.  A minimal version is
                        supplied with Qwk2Pkt.

                        You should place a name on each line.  A line is
                        considered to be a comment if it starts with a
                        semi-colon (';').

                        In general, you will want to convert names if they
                        are stored in uppercase.  Using this switch will
                        correct the names properly but does take a little
                        longer (capitalization is implied if set).

@ENDNODE
